column1: i've been meaning to read this book ever since i began working closely with students in rural schools. it's a complex environment; while many do support trump & proudly wear confederate flag sweatshirts to school
column4: pro-choice…& all complex. i began to wonder what it means to grow up queer in a rural environment.

column2: gray investigates the lives of rural queer youths in kentucky. i think one of the most important points for me was that while a lot of urban queer activism/culture revolves around a politics of visibility & a celebration of difference
column3: rural communities often operate around a valuation of familiarity & sameness. so rural queer youths use this language of sameness to assert their existence & claim to rights while still accessing things like food
column6: gray interviews teens about doing drag at walmart
column7: finding trans identification on the discovery channel
column8: exploring their sexuality through chat rooms
column9: & fighting for gsas at their local schools. i am always astounded by the strength & ingenuity of young people.

column1: 265046;instagram;2018-11-01 00:00:34;FALSE;"african women cyclists have so many obstacles to overcome in their quest to achieve their dreams sadly add sexual harassment and assault to the list

only once have i heard this beautiful soul broken... “kim why is my life always so hard?” this said as she barricaded herself behind a locked door while a brutal senegalese man tried to break through and break her. his brother and sister had given this soul a place to lay her head and left her to the wolf
column2: the brother who only wanted to steal her body and soul. she escaped in the middle of the night .

column1: i heard her sobbing whispers over whatsapp during her night of terror. the fear the exhaustion the panic
“kim why is my life always so hard? i just want to be a professional cyclist that’s all i’ve ever wanted it is dream it is serious my heart”

she is safe for now but this was too close a call. through all her fight she is still at the mercy of those who just want to take from her. as loud as she screams as loud as i scream for her there is little notice. she has no voice as a young
column3: black woman racing in europe. i cannot bare to tell her this educated
column4: financially stable american white woman has no voice either. i am her ideal of strength but i cannot tell her everyday i wake up fearful for her and girls in rwanda and elsewhere who because of their dreams to break through cultural barriers and stereotypes put them at risk for exploitation. i cannot protect them

column7: we showed the world that this behavior is absolutely unacceptable. we forced people to stop

column3: our abusers no longer hold power over us. we pledge to no longer fear defeat

column1: 265061;instagram;2018-11-01 00:07:17;FALSE;"zoë kravitz opens up about being sexually harassed by a director when she was 19 and bill cosby’s “sinister” energy - blogged by: @raquelharristv
in the midst of more women becoming comfortable with telling their #metoo stories
column2: the latest woman to speak out is actress #zoekravitz.

column1: kravitz will appear on the cover of rolling stone’s november issue. during an interview
column2: she discussed recreating her mother’s iconic photo shoot
column3: her memories of #billcosby and when she was sexually harassed by a director at the age of 19.

column1: without naming the director she went into detail about her experience being sexually harassed. “i definitely worked with a director who made me very uncomfortable. i was young — maybe 19 or 20 — and we were on location
column2: staying at the same hotel. and it was full-on: ‘can i come inside your room?’ just totally inappropriate
column3: ” kravitz said. “and then he’d do things like come to the makeup trailer and touch my hair. or say
column4: ‘let me see your costume — turn around?’ it’s just never ok for someone to do that. especially when they’re in a position of power.”

column1: kravitz then spoke on her memory of bill cosby. kravitz’s mother
column3: starred as one of cosby’s tv daughters (denise) on the show. when bonet became pregnant with kravitz in 1988
column4: bonet says cosby was “very upset.” kravitz added that she referred to cosby as “mr. righteous” and that she always felt a “type of sinister

column2: ” kravitz told rolling stone. “whether he was attracted to her
column3: or he resented her having a mind of her own

column4: ‘let me see your costume — turn around?’ it’s just never ok for someone to do that. especially when they’re in a position of power.”

column2: given it was being taken out of context:

column1: then pulled my own name out. so i feel as though there are two china cabinets - one that holds the few remaining artefacts of trauma
column2: and a second that’s slowly filling with artefacts of pleasure and sacred experience. a very interesting sliding doors to have experienced. now to consider it alongside my other poem. .

265116;instagram;2018-10-31 22:19:21;FALSE;so thankful for my meeting with ms. debbie walsh this afternoon at @womenandpolitics! 🙏 we discussed the ways in which #yearofthewoman2018 is both similar and different to the progress of 1992, new policies that might enable more women to run for office today (and old stereotypes and hurdles still holding women back), how #metoo shattered the silence on sexual violence against women and enabled women to bring experiences of abuse or violence into politics. we talked about dr. christine blasey ford, hillary clinton, the ultimate glass ceiling (and potential candidates who could shatter it in the future) - and we talked about the importance of continuing to tap women on the shoulder and make them ready to run in elections to come. 💪there is so much at stake going forward in regards to women's rights (not least abortion rights), lgbt-rights and discrimination in the work place. these #midterms2018 matter. politics matters. ✊ you may say that you don't do politics - but history has certainly taught us that politics will be done to you. ⚖️ so you might as well engage - vote, lead, or run! column1: this is nai palm...one of my musical influences.  she’s a sing-songwriter
column4: and has an incredible voice.  seriously
column5: she’s very dope.  i don’t like all her songs but the ones i do i really love...like put on repeat.  i’ve been a fan for a minute but it was her story that made me give her my influence. .

column1: she lost her mom to cancer at a very early age and was separated from her five siblings.  she was raised by her aunt who cultivated her love of music
column3: and her love of r&b/soul music (if you hear her voice you’ll know why). her music is rich with her pain
column5: and she means every bit of it when she sings.  she literally wears whatever she wants and has a style that is completely her own.  she’s a big advocate for women loving their bodies (check out her video on okayplayer). the woman is fierce and she has my influence and has inspired me both as an artist and a person.

column1: influence is so very important...make sure you give it to people that are worthy of it.  they don’t have to be perfect and i’m not saying they have to be famous but i’m saying they should inspire and encourage you to be you.  cuz if you’ve given somebody your influence you’ve given them a great gift...one that should never be taken advantage of.  and if they don’t make you feel connected
column3: or inspired...they’re not being given your influence...they’re taking it. ✊🏾💜

column1: 265130;instagram;2018-10-31 22:32:04;FALSE;"*trigger warning: this post is about sexual abuse so scroll if you are particularly sensitive to this topic.*⠀

column2: i had the honor of interviewing 3x olympic gold medalist
column3: now attorney and founder of champion women

column1: this was a tough tale to tell
column2: but an important one. we went deep on her time at duke and the day she was raped on a trail run. swimming became her main outlet to deal with the trauma and now she's become one of the most influential title ix advocates in our country today. her work is largely focused on protecting athletes against sexual abuse in sport. she successfully helped push out the last president of the usoc after the larry nassar scandal and is one of the main women responsible for the passage of the safesport act.⠀

column1: thank you nancy for being willing to go deep with me. thank you @playerstribune for sharing her story and thank you @ashlyrob for the excellent editing.⠀

column2: to disclose or discuss trauma with me. i am grateful that i’ve created a safe enough space for people to feel they can share with me
column3: and all i can say is that i am so sorry. i am sorry you are hurting. i am sorry there is so much pain in the world and i’m sorry there are people out there who want to put that pain under a magnifying glass so often.

column1: the news can be so re-traumatizing. our social circles and offices can be triggering. i get it. but know this
column2: there are people out there who love you and care about you and get you. if you need a safe space to talk or connect
column3: i can offer you @breakingfreefoundation. vulnerability and connection is what we do best. we have to free meet-ups in november: november 7th at serenity now wellness
column4: and november 14th at @thecommonsyyc. both start at 7pm

column1: 265146;instagram;2018-10-31 21:05:42;FALSE;"1984. mention that and the first response will likely be: george orwell. even when the audience is indian. which
column2: as the famous writer himself would confess
there are those who bear witness
column4: because what the world doesn’t remember
column5: it will not care for. because 34 years later
column6: there remain survivors of the genocide that occurred in delhi when
column8: a big tree was felled. fast forward to the present: justice?! remind me who exactly are these “chaurasiye”?

column1: in so many ways the mechanics of the “1984 anti-sikh riots” — we’re good at euphemisms— echoed the violence of partition. and in both
column2: women’s bodies became the battlefield. i grew up with stories of one
column3: i lived through the horror of another. and as i grew
column4: i hoped that i would put these stories out of my mind
column5: in the manner of my countrymen and women. but i couldn’t. so i wrote my next novel
column6: the radiance of a thousand suns. because i had to bear witness. because sometimes fiction is a way to tell the inconvenient truth.

column1: the novel releases in 2019 and i hope you will read it and bear witness with me. can one story change minds? do people care? are my words going to matter?
i don’t know. but i can try.

column1: 265147;instagram;2018-10-31 21:33:53;FALSE;"do you think about the wreckage that the women in your life carry inside of them?
do you think about the pain that our hearts bear?

column3: the messy truth of our existence?

column1: my heart is heavy with violence.
it seems that to be a woman means to be broken.
i call myself a “survivor” but most days i am the leftovers of what didn’t kill me.
sometimes i wish that it had.
it is hard to carry this wreckage inside of me. i call it “wreckage” because there is no other poetic name for the breaking.
for the bloody mess that the unwelcome hands made of this body.
i say “this body” because it still doesn’t feel like mine.
still doesn’t feel like the home i was promised it would be when i was little.
another woman spills her truth and the boy steps over the mess.
another woman says me too and the world talks over her
another woman is standing on stage in front of the world and the world turns off her mic.
and you wonder why our voices are hoarse.
why our skin is split open.
you wonder why i am still yelling about feminism as a new generation of girls begin to bleed.

as the sharp edges of the world reveal that womanhood is just another word for violence.";;en;;;;;;0;;dandelions.and.recovery;Anna May;;0;False;9;0;0;147;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/426b780fc7cfb5932a5c0b6ce983f23e/5D135468/t51.2885-15/e35/43705879_323966085064012_8998193650275903791_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"do you think about the wreckage that the women in your life carry inside of them?

column1: 265167;instagram;2018-10-31 21:42:27;FALSE;"“as i establish myself more on the stand-up comedy scene here in nyc
column2: i noticed that the voices of women
column4: are drowned out a lot. i’ve met a lot of people
column6: who told me that the #metoo movement is just a way for attention depraved women to get money and fame. one of my supervisors told me she thinks women who wait to come forward are vile and horrible and selfish for ruining a man’s career. as a sexual assault survivor who didn’t even process what happened to me until a full year later
column7: it was hard to hear someone i worked for undermine my experience like that. it took me months of therapy and an obscene amount of medications to convince myself that what happened was real and that i wasn’t crazy for feeling traumatized. all that progress can unravel almost entirely when people just nonchalantly say things like that to you.

column2: abby was raised in wealthy upper-class white neighborhoods. “still
column3: i had a perpetual identity crisis growing up with people who didn’t look like me or share my experiences. my name isn’t even abby
column5: but my pre-school teacher assigned me the name abby because ‘no one could pronounce my real name
column6: ’ despite the fact that it’s spelled exactly like it sounds.

column1: being an indian girl i’ve only recently learned to speak up and demand what i deserve. i just hope people will listen instead of speaking over people who feel marginalized. the amount of times white men have spoken over me to tell me that the stand-up scene in new york doesn’t have a race or misogyny problem is frustrating. wanting to share your story is only half the job
column2: people should also want to have to listen.” #chasingcolorproject";;en;#MeToo

column6: trying to catch up but it can’t connect the dots

column20: the impossible task to make him happy

column1: 265183;instagram;2018-10-31 19:05:11;FALSE;"rolling back into the rockies of the western us
column2: we meet one of my favourites – the inspiring
column3: empowered and superhero youth coach – emily argyle.

column1: i first met emily in hawaii of all places – amazing
column2: i know. we were there for hawaii food & wine fest 2016 with julie reiner. at the time
column3: emily was working at julie’s clover club bar in brooklyn

column1: 265370;instagram;2018-10-31 18:19:40;FALSE;"and for those of us african feminists who believe in god
column2: we'd like to add that our god is an unapologetically black african woman who speaks her truth and doesn't let the world get to her cause she knows she is in charge

column1: one thing i would always say is that until we can say god is a woman without people giving us a side eye
column2: our revolution won't be complete. even so called ""feminist"" men have told me they agree with everything i say but don't agree with me calling god a  woman

column1: this is because they know that by us not just drawing inspiration from the divine but linking our pronouns to her
column2: it shatters the belief that our oppression is god ordained regardless of what is seen in religious books. whenever people ask me how i reconcile my faith and feminism
column3: one thing i would always say is this: ""why would god take her time creating me only to give men permission to treat me wrongly for how she created me? there must be an error in transmission or something amiss in religious books or to put it simply plain old  sexism""

column1: at the end my god is a black african woman. i'd love to get your thoughts on this. why are people against calling god a woman? if you are a feminist with a faith
column2: how do you marry the two? even more important how do you conceptualize your god? comment below

column2: who has been with vida since february 2018. she is currently an editorial assistant for the vida review. valerie is a feminist literary critic who works on contemporary poetry and disability studies
column3: and has always admired vida's mission. she first got involved a few years ago
column4: after they published her report from the field on elena ferrante's novels and the marginalization of working-class women in academia. valerie felt that the publication process was so inclusive
column6: and thoughtful from start to finish that it inspired her to volunteer. her work with vida also carries over into her full-time job as a program officer
column7: where she helps design and administer fellowship programs for humanities scholars. she says that ""vida's values and practices shape my thinking every day--whether i'm figuring out ways to amplify the work of historically marginalized scholars
column8: or thinking critically about how different fields collect and present data on gender disparities in the academy"". valerie says fellow vida's have become her friends
column9: and are troves of knowledge and opinions about all sorts of topics: podcasts
column13: more. she says ""each time i hear about a fellow vida's latest accomplishment
column14: it's always followed by a surge of yeses and congrats and applause emojis and tweets and warmth
column15: and it's a beautiful thing to behold."" valerie says"" our work makes me think of the end of juliana spahr's poem 'tradition.' these days
column18: news that you get from poetry
column20: testimony) on to others feels difficult and dangerous
column21: because it *is* difficult and dangerous. but passing words to each other

column29: who has been with vida since february 2018. she is currently an editorial assistant for the vida review. valerie is a feminist literary critic who works on contemporary poetry and disability studies
column30: and has always admired vida's mission. she first got involved a few years ago
column31: after they published her report from the field on elena ferrante's novels and the marginalization of working-class women in academia. valerie felt that the publication process was so inclusive
column33: and thoughtful from start to finish that it inspired her to volunteer. her work with vida also carries over into her full-time job as a program officer
column34: where she helps design and administer fellowship programs for humanities scholars. she says that ""vida's values and practices shape my thinking every day--whether i am figuring out ways to amplify the work of historically marginalized scholars
column35: or thinking critically about how different fields collect and present data on gender disparities in the academy"". valerie says fellow vida's have become her friends
column36: and are troves of knowledge and opinions about all sorts of topics: podcasts

column1: 265425;instagram;2018-10-31 17:57:26;FALSE;"i hate the idea of living separate lives.
the notion of contorting myself in particular ways to fit in or not wreck somebody else’s sense of comfort.
the concept of being something for someone and another thing for someone else.
i want to be me in all times
i am giving myself full permission for exploration and the freedom of flow in whatever direction my body
column4: or mind wants to go in at a particular time.

column2: i’ve been me the whole time in front of all people... and i want to do it even more.

column5: to not have it all figured out.

column1: i am giving myself full and deeper permission to be whatever i want in any moment:
i don’t give a damn if that makes me complicated.
i no longer mind being an enigma.
i don’t need to shrink myself into a box so i’m easier to be understood or consumed.
i don’t want it or need it.
some might say being more real or raw about what’s up on my accounts would deter away clients or people i’m meant to help from wanting to invest in working with me...
and what i say to that is:
if someone is actually turned off by my authenticity than we’re not supposed to work together.
and i’d rather us both know that now and save us both time
column4: than spend any time faking it.

column1: megha sharma told that she wanted cigarettes and hence called the watchman to get her a few to which he refused saying that he was on duty. she then asked the watchman if he could send any of the three to four security guards to get her cigarettes to which she was refused again.
she went down and got herself a smoke but she also talked to the guard as to why could he not have asked one of the watchmen to go.
she then told an ani reporter that the guard threw a fit and went on to call her 'characterless' and comment upon her attire. she added that he said
column2: ""we are not here to treat you like a princess."" infuriated by this
column3: she hit him. another watchman joined the argument shortly and started hurling abuses at her. it was then that she herself called the police and a team from oshiwara police station arrived within 10 minutes and rest what happened you can see in the video

meet dr. samantha montano! she is a visiting assistant professor in demndsu. dr. montano is involved in many different aspects of emergency management but one area she’s most passionate about is the involvement of women in emergency management.

here’s how you can catch up with some of the work she’s done in this area: - she co-authored a paper on the role of gender throughout the disaster life cycle published in the journal of emergency management. - she guest co-hosted the dukes of hazards podcast and discussed the experiences of women who work in emergency management and was interviewed on the disaster politics podcast about the role of the #metoo movement in emergency management
column2: systemic barriers women face in the profession
column3: and the importance of building a profession that is representative of the communities they serve. - she regularly volunteers with middle/high school students through science education programs like skype-a-scientist and expanding your horizons. these programs have the dual benefit of teaching kids about emergency management and also showing them that although em is a male dominated field women do belong. the importance of this representation was recently validated with a comment left on photos of a recent event. a woman noted she never considered emergency management was a career option for her because she had not seen women doing that work. (swipe through to the last photo.) #smem #ndsu";;en;#MeToo

column1: she went on to tell me how she started working out after the third time it happened. she wanted to be able to fight back. the next time it happened she hit back at him with her new found strength
column2: toppled him over and warned him that she would thrash him senseless if he ever did this to her again. this was enough to shock him into compliance but only for another 5 years. even this wasn't enough to put a permanent end to it and the cycle of abuse continued.

column1: her young daughter clung on to her sari as she narrated all of this to me in a hushed tone. she was not okay being treated this way but divorce was not an option and she wanted my advice on what to do next. i felt what i feel every time i hear yet another person share their story of abuse - helpless
column2: angry and frustrated. all i could offer at that point was a patient ear
column3: my non-judgement and a sense of complete understanding of what she was going through. i could not 'save' her. i haven't been able to save anyone till date.

column1: i write this because very few of us will ever be able to 'save' someone. but what each one of us can do is to this - provide a safe space
column4: men and children to be heard. to be able to share what they are experiencing without the fear of being the odd one out
column6: the 'unlucky' one. there is strength in numbers and when we stop feeling alone in our experience
column7: it becomes easier to dismiss our own denial
column9: to ask for help even. these are the first steps to helping someone save them self and we can all be a part of it.

column1: 265444;instagram;2018-10-31 17:07:44;FALSE;"i overheard a conversation between a policeman and some security guards talking about a time they encountered a woman who had been sexually assaulted. the first thing i heard was “i knew she was lying from the beginning and i can tell you how.” i was immediately disgusted. one went on to poke holes in her story with his own opinions and they even shared a few laughs about the topic at hand.
it may be hard for some to believe the truth but that doesn’t change the fact that no matter how a story sounds
column2: an assault still could’ve happened. my own story that i’ve beaten myself up over for years probably wouldn’t make some people’s “idea” of how they think assault “should” go. i’m sure one could poke just as many holes in it.

column1: i remember going to speak to a detective about what happened to turn in my statement. at first he was kind
column2: as time went on and i explained every detail
column3: he changed. i could tell he didn’t believe me himself. his retort was very sarcastic
column5: and he spoke to me as if i was lying. i immediately said i changed my mind and wouldn’t go through with anything and got up to leave. in that moment it’s already hard enough to be open about something like that and then to have someone treat you like that makes it even harder. i do get why many that are sexually assaulted deal in silence. i did. i internalized every single bit of it. 🔸🔸

column1: for those who have been assaulted be strong and speak up still. be stronger than i was even though it’s hard. even when you’re doubted or made out to be a liar or even when you think your story doesn’t sound believable. to those who are on the other side
column2: i know it’s hard to decipher when someone is telling the truth or if they’re really fabricating a story. sometimes there may be hard evidence and sadly sometimes there isn’t. survivors have already endured enough so to come to speak up about it
column3: takes a large amount of courage. support coming forward and speaking out without judgment.

column15: #Therapy;;;;;0;;collaterallydamaged_;💡 Mental Health blog.;;0;False;7;0;0;56;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/3c8f8a5cac753c5efda2bfefa98914cb/5D053E0C/t51.2885-15/e35/43334328_1989129431176919_2808717621205577800_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"i overheard a conversation between a policeman and some security guards talking about a time they encountered a woman who had been sexually assaulted. the first thing i heard was “i knew she was lying from the beginning and i can tell you how.” i was immediately disgusted. one went on to poke holes in her story with his own opinions and they even shared a few laughs about the topic at hand.

column1: it may be hard for some to believe the truth but that doesn’t change the fact that no matter how a story sounds
column2: an assault still could’ve happened. my own story that i’ve beaten myself up over for years probably wouldn’t make some people’s “idea” of how they think assault “should” go. i’m sure one could poke just as many holes in it.

column1: i remember going to speak to a detective about what happened to turn in my statement. at first he was kind
column2: as time went on and i explained every detail
column3: he changed. i could tell he didn’t believe me himself. his retort was very sarcastic
column5: and he spoke to me as if i was lying. i immediately said i changed my mind and wouldn’t go through with anything and got up to leave. in that moment it’s already hard enough to be open about something like that and then to have someone treat you like that makes it even harder. i do get why many that are sexually assaulted deal in silence. i did. i internalized every single bit of it. 🔸🔸

column1: for those who have been assaulted be strong and speak up still. be stronger than i was even though it’s hard. even when you’re doubted or made out to be a liar or even when you think your story doesn’t sound believable. to those who are on the other side
column2: i know it’s hard to decipher when someone is telling the truth or if they’re really fabricating a story. sometimes there may be hard evidence and sadly sometimes there isn’t. survivors have already endured enough so to come to speak up about it
column3: takes a large amount of courage. support coming forward and speaking out without judgment.

column1: 265448;instagram;2018-10-31 17:08:15;FALSE;"shannon is standing at the door to jefferson county community ministries where she volunteers her time as a recovery coach. i always have a hard time pulling a paragraph out of someone’s addiction story
column3: i’ll tell you what set her heart-breaking story of addiction in motion
column4: then let you read in her own words some of what transpired along the way.

column1: shannon was sexually abused by her stepbrother when she was younger. when she came forward
column2: her stepmother did not believe her and accused her of trying to ruin her marriage
column3: so nothing came of it. shannon eventually confronted her abuser when she was an adult
column4: but he denied it and called her crazy since by that time she had fallen to the depths of addiction.

column1: read so much more of shannon’s story on my 52 addicts section of my blog (link in profile). follow along on my journey to meet 52 people who have struggled with addiction. visit the link in our profile for more info on this project

column1: it was a normal day. with all the rush of closing metro rail doors i took a leap inside. probably my biggest mistake.
with all the commotion the crowd had already pushed a girl out at front and i collided right against her.
in all that phase i probably didn't realise that my hand had rested on her breasts for a brief moment.
with a jerk i tried to move back but the crowd had left no space to move. but her scream made some space and so did her slap. i noticed a few cameras were already pointing towards us.
i'm really sorry i never meant to collide with you
column3: i tried blurting out but in vain as it was interrupted by yet another slap.

column1: she screamed at me and people kept looking. glaring at me whereas almost everybody had seen what was the real thing. but neither they tried to deny the accusations nor was i allowed to.

column2: an innocent was framed as a molester. -

column1: i'm actually a big supporter of #metoo as that gives immense power to the ladies. however
column3: 'with great power comes great responsibility' it becomes the responsibility of a lady to judge a person whom she is about to frame.

column1: raise your voice against harassment. it need not be sexual alone. however
column2: please try not to frame an innocent once. your few words will ruin someone's life.

column1: as a guy i can tell you that there are many guys who are genuinely in those circumstances where they are caught up in moments where they seem guilty but aren't.
don't let the good guys develop a fear for a lady.

column2: i would have wanted to be her. karaba the sorceress. she's a character from an animated movie called kirikou and the sorceress. i used to hate her when i was a child
column3: because ahe was the villain of the story
column5: kidnapping all the men. she was cold

column2: nobody had ever bothered to ask why she was this way
column3: except a little boy who asked his grandpa. he was told that karaba was once a young beautiful woman who was kidnapped by a group of men
column4: who held her down while one of them inserted a thorn down her back. it has never been removed
column5: and the pain has made her heartless.

column1: i then read that the script writer of this movie insinuated that this was a rape story
column2: and he wanted to display how the abuse of women stalls the progression of society
column3: or at least we should be aware that it does. this is why nothing grows around the home of karaba
column4: and the village hasn't made much progress because karaba has kidnapped the men. she is also so paranoid and traumarised that she has transformed the men into talking statues that are now sentinels who look out miles away to make sure no one sneaks up on her.

column1: karaba isn't healed until the little boy resolves to go take the thorn out of hed back. while everyone else wants to defeat her
column2: he wants to end her pain. and by ending her pain
column4: as in he instantly grows taller and older. .

column1: i love this character because she represented so many sexual assault survivors who years after the act
column2: still carry the trauma like a thorn in their back. but i also love that the movie insisted that nothing will ever be right in the society  until you right this wrong. it was a demand for accountability. a #metoo moment if you will.

column5: but i knew in my heart that i had to do everything in my power to complete the race. the worldly assault continued to the end

column1: 265694;instagram;2018-10-31 13:37:49;FALSE;"amalie emmy noether(23 march 1882 – 14 april 1935) was a german mathematician who made important contributions to abstract algebra and theoretical physics.
she was described by pavel alexandrov
column4: hermann weyl and norbert wiener as the most important woman in the history of mathematics.

column1: as one of the leading mathematicians of her time
column2: she developed the theories of rings
noether's theorem explains the connection between symmetry and conservation laws.

column1: noether was born to a jewish family in the franconian town of erlangen; her father was a mathematician

column1: 265748;instagram;2018-10-31 13:18:35;FALSE;"i spent the last four days assisting jaiya ma and ian ferguson at path to passion
column2: their live entry-level event to introduce attendees to the erotic blueprints™. biggest yet: over 220 humans joining together to learn and support one another in acceptance of our whole
though: that what we do personally
column3: creates our collective reality. it matters that jaiya and ian and those of us on this team are doing the work to create an intentional
column4: safe container where i and every one of these people can show up and share all of ourselves. without shame. without hiding. without pretending. grounded in our bodies.

column1: it matters that they lead by example. that they bring all of themselves and show up in imperfection
column4: owning messiness and confusion and moving through all that
column6: into clarity and acceptance and power and purpose and love.

column1: it matters that this was about sex
column2: about our sexual selves and our confusion and our awesomeness and our complexity and our pleasure. it’s not self-indulgence. it is what feeds our deepest selves and creates permission for us to be real and alive out in the world
column3: so we can maybe for the first time really show up for our families

column1: it matters that so much of our work was about consent
especially now. especially with #metoo and conversations about consent and inclusivity and confusion about what power is and should be in the world
column2: in governments and social networks and day to day interactions.

column1: what if it is okay for us to find out
column3: who we are? to be who we are? all the time? everywhere?

column1: i had the opportunity to share my story as it is: real
column4: full of intention and mistakes and pleasure and growth and love and transformation. to hear the stories of others

column1: 265841;instagram;2018-10-31 11:20:09;FALSE;"perhaps the most famous confession in all of scripture. david comes before the lord after his assault of bathsheba and the murder of her husband uriah. nathan the prophet has challenged and convicted him and david now sees the error of his ways. we all know the story - but do we live it?
david’s path to repentance and restoration was painful and it was costly but today we want quick and easy forgiveness
column2: what german theologian dietrich bonhoeffer called “cheap grace.” but what david’s prayer reveals to us here is that cheap grace doesn’t save. easy forgiveness does not blow out our sin. what is required is the merciful presence of christ to not only forgive
column3: but to cleanse and purify. we need to possess a broken heart and contrite spirit before the lord and those we have sinned against and be willing to humble ourselves as david does. in the age of #metoo and similar movements we are starting to hear a lot of formal confessions from perpetrators in the media. most of them are poor attempts at crisis management and they are directed at seeking cheap grace from their fans or followers
column4: but rarely do you see anyone confess or repent like this. in the church

column1: 265847;instagram;2018-10-31 11:24:18;FALSE;"the #metoo movement is finally arriving in india. it started off recently when a bollywood actress spoke out about the sexual harassment and intimidation she faced at the hands of a prominent actor from the industry. and it’s been a whirlwind ever since with women from all walks of life journalism
column4: law coming out with their own stories. such is the furore that a cabinet minister accused of sexual harassment stepped down from his post.

column1: in the light of this our founder koshika krishna ( @sanskariaurat ) has launched a nationwide petition through change.org india asking two indian ministries (women and child/ corporate affairs) “to instruct all companies to make public their anti sexual harassment members on their websites” ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

with the aim that access to information will pave the way towards securing justice for the survivors and with the belief that this process will ensure a better implementation of the sexual harassment at workplace act in india. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
#we need your support! please sign and share. let’s #cleanupworkplaces ! (1/2) #seher_india";;en;#MeToo

column1: 265877;instagram;2018-10-31 10:46:54;FALSE;"day 31 of domestic violence month. i wanted to share my light at the end of such a long dark tunnel. my now husband came into my life when my scars of my facial reconstructive surgery had faded away from the public eye.  one month after i met him
column2: my mother allowed me and my children to come live with her again after i begged her to give me just one year. i was  embarrassed i felt like a failure.  during that year we began dating. my mother told me that no man wants to be with a woman that has children by someone else. i called him and ask him if he had a problem with me having children by someone else? he said ""no"" and asked ""where was this coming from?"" i told him
column3: his tone of voice was calm but in disbelief he responded "" don't listen to her
column4: your children are a reflection of you and i love you so there for i love them"". my mother almost made me miss out on my husband!

column1: the more i think about the unmotherly things she would say to me i now know that my mother was just deflecting her insecurities on to me.
almost 16 years later my husband has been loving on me. god  sent me someone who had so much patience and love to assist him with such a broken
column2: damage woman. loving me was not easy and trust me when i say i've put this man through a lot. he saw pass my flaws and straight to my heart. he would constantly say i have such a good heart but that i was angry and needed to learn how to let go and forgive. i did just that. i forgave my parents and my abuser and now i'm here sharing my story of survival and hope to women who are suffering in silence. don't let your abuser have you miss out on your light at the end of your tunnel. 💜💜💜💜💜💜💙💙💙💙💙";;en;;;;;;0;;mrstingle;Chevonne Tingle;;0;False;18;0;0;66;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/a0e322bfb38e6b86f38464bc99a6d2fd/5D21540E/t51.2885-15/e35/43985746_2130236963893335_9211471605895528448_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"day 31 of domestic violence month. i wanted to share my light at the end of such a long dark tunnel. my now husband came into my life when my scars of my facial reconstructive surgery had faded away from the public eye.  one month after i met him

column1: 265886;instagram;2018-10-31 10:54:18;FALSE;"we’ve got suze from @theachopsbooks joining us for this week’s #lwlbookclub to chat about her new book the queen engineer and her mission to give fairytales a much needed makeover.
tell us about your new book?
the queen engineer is about a princess called florence
column2: who loves maths and science and dreams of becoming an engineer. her father
column4: thinks she should be happy growing up to become queen
column5: so flo sets out to show him what she's capable of
column6: and why everyone should be able to follow their dreams.

column1: what inspired you to write the queen engineer?

column2: it was to see if i could rewrite traditional fairy tales to change the messages that children receive. i wanted to take this idea and write about a princess who wanted more than just a prince to save her. i also loved the idea of encouraging girls to consider maths
column3: engineering and science as a career choice. i like that flo wears more than one hat in life
column4: a crown and a hard hat
column5: which all of us do! none of us is just one thing in life
column6: so why limit children to just one hat?

column1: why was it important to you to shake up the fairy tale genre?

it was only reading and watching fairytales as an adult that i realised the messages were potentially damaging. children take everything in books and movies very literally. if girls spend their childhood learning that they must be beautiful and gentle
column2: how likely is it that they'll grow up to realise that their value lies in more than just their looks? and it's not just girls; little boys grow up believing they have to be strong; people tell them not to run / throw / cry like a girl which teaches them that being a girl is inferior and that they can't show any emotion. we live in a time where 84 men a week commit suicide as they live their lives believing they should 'man up' rather than seek help. we're also experiencing a shift in society with #metoo and #timesup; if little boys are taught that girls are their equals
column3: and that there's nothing inferior about being a girl
column4: they will hopefully grow up to become young men who stand side by side women in the future.

265918;instagram;2018-10-31 10:07:54;FALSE;"🔶 حتما شنیده اید که برخی هر چه می خورند سیر نمی شوند و باید مرتب چیزی را ببلعند. علت این بیماری تورم زیاد اثنی عشر و میکروب #هلیکوباکترپیلوری است که باعث می شود مرتب شیره معده تولید شود و احساس گرسنگی از بین نرود. 🔶 امروزه درمان تورم اثنی عشر را در یک دوره یک ماهه انجام می دهند. اما ظاهرا این بیماری در انواع جدید خود هرگز در #کره درمان نمی شود!! 🔶️با اینکه در #کره_جنوبی با انواع الکل و فیلم های کذایی و... به راحتی می توان مثلا بی قیدی را تجربه کرد، اما هرگز جوان هایشان سیر نمی شوند و روز به روز ارضای جنسی جوانان کره ای سخت می شود. این جوانان در خیابان و اماکن خصوصی به صورت مخفیانه از زن ها و در حالات مختلف عکس می گیرند و در سایت های مستهجن اقدام به پخش آن می کنند. 🔶️حالا آنقدر این بیماری روانی عکس مخفی از زنان در کره که #بالاترین_نرخ_خودکشی_در_دنیا را دارد زیاد شده که زنان این کشور بزرگترین تظاهرات زنانه تاریخ کره را برپا کردند تا به وضع بی بند و باری و عدم توجه مسوولین ذی ربط شکایت کنند. .

در تصویر اول یک زن کره ای بنری را به دست گرفته که رویش نوشته: ""زندگی من لذت جنسی تو نیست"" و در تصویر دوم نوشته: ""زنان عصبانی دنیا را تغییر می دهند"". 🔶️ این حرکت بعد از حرکت جهانی #metoo و با انتخاب نام #molka به عنوان دومین حرکت بزرگ ضد سوء استفاده جنسی از زنان شناخته می شود. . 🔶️ میکروب هلیکوباکترپیلوری را جدی بگیرید! باز هم اخباری از آن را در کشورهای مختلف به زودی منتشر می کنیم. .
💥 ۲۰۲۵ اولین کانال  تخصصی حقایق فیلتر شده جهان
